<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="31" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Morphological description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="31">
Frustules are usually low to high-cylindrical, valve face flat. Valve is 16.6 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
in diameter, 4.4 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
high, number of areolae lines on valve bend 15 in 10 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
, in the line 18 areolae in 10 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
. Ringleiste is wide, linking spines are large, sharpened (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. LM (A, B) and SEM (C-H) images of species found in the transitional zone at Mykolaiv city: A Aulacoseira islandica, valve view B Aulacoseira nivalis, valve view C Aulacoseira subarctica, girdle view of complete frustule D-H Actinocyclus normanii valve view (D pseudonodulus shown with arrow, E, G) and girdle view (H, F). Scale bars: 10 μm." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.178.64426.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545735" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">3C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="31" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="31">
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="" class="Coscinodiscophyceae" family="Aulacoseiraceae" genus="Aulacoseira" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Aulacoseira subarctica" order="Aulacoseirales" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="subarctica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Aulacoseira subarctica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a planktonic alga in lakes, rivers, reservoirs and temporary water bodies and is confined to higher latitudes. It usually appears in response to moderate increases in nutrients, supposedly to phosphorus concentrations controlling its presence and is disadvantaged by further enrichment (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/0967026031000094102" author="Chris, E" journalOrPublisher="European Journal of Phycology" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" pagination="83 - 101" refId="B21" refString="Chris, E, Gibson, N, Anderson, J, Haworth, EY, 2003. Aulacoseira subarctica: Taxonomy, physiology, ecology and palaeoecology. European Journal of Phycology 38 (2): 83 - 101, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/0967026031000094102" title="Aulacoseira subarctica: Taxonomy, physiology, ecology and palaeoecology." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/0967026031000094102" volume="38" year="2003">Chris et al. 2003</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="31" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="31">
Occurred in the Southern Bug River in Mykolaiv city (near Varvarivskyi Bridge) (Table 
<tableCitation captionStart="Table 1" captionStartId="T1" captionText="Table 1. Species composition of centric diatoms at the investigated sites near Mykolaiv city in the Southern Bug River in the year 2017 (2013 added for station 2)." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DD3AC92F3D14B9FD95B22148C16CA677" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" tableUuid="DD3AC92F3D14B9FD95B22148C16CA677">1</tableCitation>
). This species is known from the Dnipro River basin (
<bibRefCitation author="Tsarenko, PM" journalOrPublisher="Gantner Verlag, Ruggell" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" refId="B127" refString="Tsarenko, PM, Wasser, SP, Nevo, E, 2009. Algae of Ukraine: diversity, nomenclature, taxonomy, ecology and geography. Vol. 2. Bacillariophyta. A.R.A. Gantner Verlag, Ruggell" title="Algae of Ukraine: diversity, nomenclature, taxonomy, ecology and geography. Vol. 2. Bacillariophyta. A. R. A." year="2009">Tsarenko et al. 2009</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="31">
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="" class="Coscinodiscophyceae" family="Aulacoseiraceae" genus="Aulacoseira" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Aulacoseira subarctica" order="Aulacoseirales" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="subarctica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Aulacoseira subarctica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is widely distributed across Europe (Germany, Great Britain, Holland, Norway, Russia, Ukraine, Scandinavia), Asia (Russia, Japan, China), North America, Australia and New Zealand. The species is rare in the tropics, and positive identifications are lacking for Africa (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/0967026031000094102" author="Chris, E" journalOrPublisher="European Journal of Phycology" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" pagination="83 - 101" refId="B21" refString="Chris, E, Gibson, N, Anderson, J, Haworth, EY, 2003. Aulacoseira subarctica: Taxonomy, physiology, ecology and palaeoecology. European Journal of Phycology 38 (2): 83 - 101, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/0967026031000094102" title="Aulacoseira subarctica: Taxonomy, physiology, ecology and palaeoecology." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/0967026031000094102" volume="38" year="2003">Chris et al. 2003</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
